data.content:
**In .NET 11, all synchronous I/O on the EF Core Cosmos DB provider is fully removed — no opt-in exists anymore.** The sync-over-async workaround you had in .NET 10 will stop working; every call to `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` will **throw at runtime**.

You must convert everything to async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- This is a **runtime** break, not a compile-time error — the code builds but throws when executed.
- The `async` change will cascade to all callers, so plan to propagate `async/await` up through controllers/services.
- `Add()` itself is fine synchronously — only the I/O operations (`SaveChanges`, queries) need async equivalents.
